<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,310,403,429]" box="[189,310,403,429]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,403,429]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,403,429]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,1399,449,582]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Antennae long, postpedicel very long (
<figureCitation box="[644,735,450,476]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[188,231,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[233,1359,267,1781]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[233,1359,267,1781]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 3. Megatrigon spp., left antenna, lateral view. A. Megatrigon argenteus (Walker, 1852) comb. nov. (♁). B. M. argentifrons sp. nov. (♁). C. M. argentimaculatus sp. nov. (♁). D. M. magnicornis sp. nov. (♁). E. M. natalensis sp. nov. (♁). F. M. sexmaculatus sp. nov. (♁). G. M. apiformis sp. nov. (♁). H. M. cooksoni sp. nov. (♁). I. M. immaculatus sp. nov. (♁). J. M. ochreatus (Hull, 1964) comb. nov. (♁). K. M. tabanoides sp. nov. (♁). L. M. jacobi (Hervé-Bazin, 1913) comb. nov. (♁). M. M. nivalis (Hull, 1964) comb. nov. (♀)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3849886" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3849886/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
), 1.9–2.2 × as long as deep, 2.4–2.75 as long as pedicel; tergites 2+3 (
<figureCitation box="[351,445,485,511]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[189,232,1862,1888]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[189,1399,265,1837]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 7. Megatrigon spp., abdomen, dorsal view, ♁. A. Megatrigon argenteus (Walker, 1852) comb. nov. B. M. argentifrons sp. nov. C. M. argentimaculatus sp. nov. D. M. magnicornis sp. nov. E. M. natalensis sp. nov. F. M. sexmaculatus sp. nov. G. M. apiformis sp. nov. H. M. cooksoni sp. nov. I. M. immaculatus sp. nov. J. M. ochreatus (Hull, 1964) comb. nov. K. M. tabanoides sp. nov. L. M. jacobi (Hervé-Bazin, 1913) comb. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3849902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3849902/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
) with small silver spots (not reaching margins of tergite, except sometimes in tergite 3) largely separated (distance between silver spots on tergites 2+3 large, 0.45–0.50 × as wide as tergite); silver spots on tergite 3 with scattered black and white setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,324,621,647]" box="[189,324,621,647]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,621,647]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,621,647]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[189,1398,667,729]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
The species epithet, which is formed as an adjective, is derived from the Latin words 
<emphasis box="[1198,1289,668,693]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">magnus</emphasis>
(= large) and 
<emphasis box="[239,319,703,728]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">cornus</emphasis>
(= horn), alluding to the long antennae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
